<HEADLINE>
<P>
VALLEY-AREA ROUNDUP; CRESCENTA VALLEY GIRLS SHAKE OFF VILLAGE CHRISTIAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVE DESMOND 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 It was near halftime when Crescenta Valley High girls' basketball Coach Marc 
Ward came to a conclusion.  
</P>
<P>
 "If Village (Christian) was going to beat us, it was going to have to be from 
the inside," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Ward extended his Falcons' defense to the perimeter at halftime and turned the 
Crusaders inside out in a 62-50 victory in a second-round game of the Thousand 
Oaks tournament Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 Junior Amirah Leonard scored 16 of her 34 points in the first quarter to help 
stake Crescenta Valley (10-3) to a 25-14 lead. 
</P>
<P>
 But the defensive adjustment was needed after Village Christian (8-3) 
connected on four consecutive three-pointers during a two-minute span of the 
second quarter, helping to close an 11-point margin to 33-30 at intermission. 
The Crusaders managed only one three-pointer in three attempts in the second 
half. While Village Christian's outside game floundered, Crescenta Valley's 
flourished. 
</P>
<P>
 Leonard, a junior guard, made five three-pointers and opened up the inside for 
the undersized Falcons. 
</P>
<P>
 "That's the best game she's ever played at C.V.," Ward said of the third-year 
varsity player. "And this was her 62nd game with us." 
</P>
<P>
 Freshman Michelle Greco added 11 points and 14 rebounds for Crescenta Valley. 
The Falcons, who started three juniors, a sophomore and Greco, outrebounded the 
Crusaders, 43-26, despite a considerable height disadvantage. 
</P>
<P>
 All-Southern Section forward Lindy James scored 21 points for Village 
Christian, 14 in the first half. Village Christian struggled against the 
Falcons' full-court pressure and committed 29 turnovers. In the first half, the 
Crusaders turned the ball over 16 times, leading to 21 Crescenta Valley points. 
</P>
<P>
 The Crusaders' third loss equals their total from last season, when they 
advanced to the Southern Section Division IV-A championship game and Southern 
California semifinals and posted a 26-3 record. 
</P>
<P>
 "I am not at all pleased with my team's effort," said Village Christian Coach 
John Domke. DAVE DESMOND 
</P>
</TEXT>
