<HEADLINE>
<P>
JOHN E. BOSWELL; HISTORIAN OF GAY MARRIAGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 John E. Boswell, a Yale historian who provoked debate with his research saying 
gay marriages during the Middle Ages were celebrated in the church, died Friday 
of the complications of AIDS. He was 47. 
</P>
<P>
 Boswell drew national attention in June with his book "Same-Sex Unions in 
Premodern Europe," a study of more than 60 manuscripts from the Middle Ages. 
</P>
<P>
 Boswell contended that homosexual marriages were well established in the 
medieval church. But Boswell's thesis was criticized by other scholars. He 
wrote that one major aim of his work was "to rebut the common idea that 
religious belief -- Christian and other -- has been the cause of intolerance in 
regard to gay people." 
</P>
<P>
 Boswell joined the Yale faculty in 1975 as an assistant professor. He was 
appointed a full professor in 1982. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Obituary; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
