<HEADLINE>
<P>
ROSE TOURNEY WARM-UPS START TODAY; LEISURE: EVENTS BEFORE THE PARADE AND GAME 
OFFER OPPORTUNITIES TO VIEW FLOATS, SEE THE STADIUM, HEAR BANDS AND TEST 
GOLFING SKILLS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LISA O'NEILL, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In case a huge parade and football game is not enough Tournament of Roses 
saturation for you, a week of Rose Bowl-related family activities will be 
offered beginning today.  
</P>
<P>
 For $1 per person per location, or $2 per person for two or more locations, 
enthusiasts can see the Rose Parade floats being decorated. They can also, for 
another $2, see the Rose Bowl stadium before the big game, decked out in the 
colors of the two Rose Bowl teams, Penn State and the University of Oregon. 
</P>
<P>
 Jack French, executive director of the Pasadena Tournament of Roses Assn., 
said organizers expect 30,000 to 50,000 people to visit one or more of the 
venues over the six-day period. 
</P>
<P>
 Proceeds will go to local charities, French said, adding that the recipients 
will be determined later. 
</P>
<P>
 "We decided we needed another event for the people in the community who might 
not get a chance to go to the Rose Bowl," French said.  
</P>
<P>
 He said the idea to expand the activities offered during the week before the 
Rose Bowl was based on a weeklong event organized by the National Football 
League the week before the Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
 Merchants will be selling their wares and Pasadena restaurants will be selling 
their cuisine at a food court and souvenir boutique throughout the week. Bands 
and dancers performing in the Rose Parade will offer special performances. 
</P>
<P>
 Here is a breakdown of events and their costs (parking is free): 
</P>
<P>
 * Float viewing, food court and souvenir boutique 
</P>
<P>
 Rose Bowl Parking Area K 
</P>
<P>
